{
  "type": "StepFunctions",
  "title": "Step Functions",
  "description": "Step Functions is a serverless orchestrator that sequences calls to AWS services using a state machine. It handles retries, error catching, parallel execution, and long-running workflows — all without writing orchestration code in your application.",
  "connections": {
    "parents": [],
    "trafficSources": [],
    "trafficTargets": [],
    "associations": ["Lambda", "ECS", "SQS", "DynamoDB", "SNS"]
  },
  "practices": [
    "Use STANDARD type for critical business workflows (orders, payments, onboarding) — exactly-once execution and full execution history are worth the cost.",
    "Use EXPRESS type for high-volume, short-lived workloads (stream processing, IoT events) where at-least-once is acceptable and cost matters.",
    "Always enable CloudWatch logging on EXPRESS machines — they have no built-in execution history, so logging is your only debuggability.",
    "Prefer SDK integrations (optimistic) over Lambda wrappers for simple DynamoDB or SQS calls — removes an unnecessary Lambda invocation and reduces latency.",
    "Design for idempotency in every task — Step Functions can retry tasks on failure, so each Lambda or ECS task must tolerate duplicate calls.",
    "Use Wait for Callback (.waitForTaskToken) for human approval steps — the state machine pauses cheaply until the callback arrives, without polling."
  ],
  "configNotes": [
    "The state machine definition (Amazon States Language JSON) lives in your Terraform — WIMCUI models the orchestration topology via association edges, not the definition.",
    "The execution role needs permissions for every service the state machine invokes — Lambda:InvokeFunction, ECS:RunTask, SQS:SendMessage, etc.",
    "STANDARD executions are charged per state transition (~$0.000025/transition). EXPRESS are charged per execution duration.",
    "Tracing (X-Ray) adds end-to-end visibility across all invoked services — recommended for production workflows."
  ],
